						               													<description>&amp;#229;&amp;#139;&amp;#135;&amp;#232;&amp;#128;&amp;#133;&amp;#229;&amp;#175;&amp;#190;&amp;#231;&amp;#173;&amp;#150;&amp;#228;&amp;#188;&amp;#154;&amp;#232;&amp;#173;&amp;#176; II (Yusha Taisaku Kaigi II) is a tactical card game from Japan, re-working &amp;#229;&amp;#139;&amp;#135;&amp;#232;&amp;#128;&amp;#133;&amp;#229;&amp;#175;&amp;#190;&amp;#231;&amp;#173;&amp;#150;&amp;#228;&amp;#188;&amp;#154;&amp;#232;&amp;#173;&amp;#176; (Yusha Taisaku Kaigi) with new rules and additional characters.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Whilst the main gameplay is the same, the players' characters now have special abilities they can use to improve their position. And the hero is now accompanied by hunters and priests to add the approach to the castle.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players take on the roles of Generals serving the Demon King. As a hero approaches to attack the Demon King's castle, the Generals must work together to defeat them. But if the hero is vanquished, a single winner is decided, based upon the strength of attack each General secretly held back in their hand.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players send monsters to attack the hero, with the monsters card showing a value in stars. The players also use dice which amend the attack, and also determine how the hero moves. The hero can use weapons and items to defeat the monsters.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;If the hero is killed, the stars left in each player's hand are totalled up for each player, with the most stars winning. If the hero reaches the castle, all the players lose. But a player can win the game by sudden death by managing to assassinate the hero in a single stroke.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
